🔹 🎯 Task 1: Describe a Number
You are writing a utility that prints a human-readable description of a number — but the method must be callable with either an int or a double.

📥 Input:
// call both overloads in main method
int    intVal;
double doubleVal;

⚙️ Requirements:
• Write an overloaded method describe that accepts an int and prints "Integer: X"
• Write another describe that accepts a double and prints "Decimal: X.XX" (always 2 decimal places)
• Call both from main

⚠️ Watch out:
• In JS you'd write one function and check typeof. In Java the compiler picks the overload at compile time based on the declared type — passing 3 to a method that has both describe(int) and describe(double) will always resolve to describe(int). There is no runtime dispatch here.

📤 Output format:
Integer: X
Decimal: X.XX

📌 Test cases:
Input: intVal=7, doubleVal=3.5
Output:
Integer: 7
Decimal: 3.50

Input: intVal=-1, doubleVal=0.1
Output:
Integer: -1
Decimal: 0.10

Input: intVal=100, doubleVal=99.999
Output:
Integer: 100
Decimal: 100.00

Input: intVal=0, doubleVal=0.0
Output:
Integer: 0
Decimal: 0.00

