 🎯 Task 3: Power Calculator
You are writing a math helper where the exponent can be omitted (defaults to 2 — squaring).
📥 Input:
double base;
int    exponent;   // used in the two-argument call
⚙️ Requirements:
•
Write power(double base) → returns base raised to the power of 2
•
Write power(double base, int exponent) → returns base raised to the power of exponent
•
Both methods must return a double
•
main prints both results with no decimal places (cast to long for printing)
⚠️ Watch out:
•
Math.pow returns a double. Casting (long) Math.pow(...) truncates, not rounds — (long) 7.9999999 = 7. Verify your test cases with exact integers to avoid float precision surprises.
•
In JS you'd use default parameters (exponent = 2). Java has no default parameters — overloading is the idiomatic substitute.
📤 Output format:
Squared: X
Power: X
📌 Test cases:
Input: base=3.0, exponent=3
Output:
Squared: 9
Power: 27

Input: base=2.0, exponent=10
Output:
Squared: 4
Power: 1024

Input: base=5.0, exponent=0
Output:
Squared: 25
Power: 1

Input: base=1.0, exponent=100
Output:
Squared: 1
Power: 1

