🔹 🎯 BONUS task: Min of Two or Three
You are implementing a min utility — the caller can compare two or three integers. The three-argument version must reuse the two-argument version internally.
📥 Input:
int a;
int b;
int c;
⚙️ Requirements:
•
Write min(int a, int b) → returns the smaller of the two
•
Write min(int a, int b, int c) → returns the smallest of the three by calling min(int, int) twice — no Math.min allowed
•
main prints results of both calls
⚠️ Watch out:
•
Java resolves the overload at compile time based on argument count. min(a, b, c) and min(a, b) are entirely different method signatures — there is no arguments object or rest-params magic like in JS.
•
A common mistake: writing min(int a, int b, int c) without delegating, then having two separate implementations that can go out of sync.
📤 Output format:
Min of two:   X
Min of three: X
📌 Test cases:
Input: a=4, b=7, c=1
Output:
Min of two:   4
Min of three: 1

Input: a=-3, b=-3, c=-3
Output:
Min of two:   -3
Min of three: -3

Input: a=0, b=-1, c=100
Output:
Min of two:   -1
Min of three: -1

Input: a=Integer.MAX_VALUE, b=Integer.MAX_VALUE - 1, c=Integer.MAX_VALUE - 2
Output:
Min of two:   2147483646
Min of three: 2147483645